question.text: A bakelite beaker has volume capacity of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>500</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cc</mi></math> at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi></math>. When it is partially filled with <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">V</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi></msub></math> volume (at <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi></math>)  of mercury, it is found that the unfilled volume of the beaker remains constant as temperature is varied. If <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi>γ</mi><mtext>bester </mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mn>0</mn><mo>°</mo><msup><mi mathvariant="normal">C</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo></math> where <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>γ</mi></math> is the coefficient of volume expansion, then  <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mi mathvariant="normal">V</mi><mi mathvariant="normal">m</mi></msub></math> (in <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mi>cc</mi></math> ) is close to <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>…</mo></math>
